### SpamFilter (Go)

Simple **Go-based spam filter** using a **bag-of-words model** and an **Enron-style email spam dataset**.  
This is a **personal hobby / learning project**, **not intended for real-world or production use**.

---

### Status / Disclaimer

- **Hobby project only**: for learning Go and basic text classification.
- **Not production-ready**: no security review, no guarantees about accuracy, robustness, or performance.
- **Do not use** as a real email filter in any critical or production environment.

---

### Project overview

This project reads email text data, tokenizes it, builds a simple **bag-of-words** representation, and applies a basic model to classify messages as spam or ham.

Main pieces of code live in:

- `main.go`: entry point / wiring.
- `bagofwords/`: bag-of-words feature logic.
- `tokenizer/` and `tokenizer/parser/`: simple text tokenization/parsing.
- `model/`: prediction logic.

---

### Dataset setup

The project uses the **Email Spam Classification dataset** from Kaggle:  
`purusinghvi/email-spam-classification-dataset`

It expects:

- A ZIP file named **`enron-spam.zip`** in the **project root**.
- An extracted directory named **`enron-spam/`** in the **project root**.

Expected layout (simplified):

```text
spamfilter/
  main.go
  bagofwords/
  tokenizer/
  model/
  enron-spam.zip
  enron-spam/
    Enron_Txt_fn.csv
    ...other dataset files...
```

#### Requirements (Kaggle API)

To use the Kaggle download URL, you need:

- A **Kaggle account**
- A **Kaggle API token** configured for the Kaggle CLI

See Kaggle’s API docs:  
[Kaggle API documentation](https://www.kaggle.com/docs/api)

In short:

1. On Kaggle, go to **Account** → **Create New API Token** to download `kaggle.json`.
2. Place `kaggle.json` in:
   - Linux / macOS: `~/.kaggle/kaggle.json`
   - Windows: `C:\Users\<YourUser>\.kaggle\kaggle.json`

---

### Download dataset as `enron-spam.zip` (project root)

All commands below assume your current working directory is the **project root** (`spamfilter/`).

#### Bash / Unix-like shell

From the project root:

```bash
curl -L -o enron-spam.zip \
  https://www.kaggle.com/api/v1/datasets/download/purusinghvi/email-spam-classification-dataset
```

#### From anywhere (absolute path)

Replace `<PROJECT_ROOT>` with the absolute path to your `spamfilter` folder:

```bash
curl -L -o "<PROJECT_ROOT>/enron-spam.zip" \
  https://www.kaggle.com/api/v1/datasets/download/purusinghvi/email-spam-classification-dataset
```

Example matching this project on Windows (Git Bash / WSL):

```bash
curl -L -o "/c/Users/DELL/Documents/Isymply/go/spamfilter/enron-spam.zip" \
  https://www.kaggle.com/api/v1/datasets/download/purusinghvi/email-spam-classification-dataset
```

---

### Unzip to `enron-spam/` in project root

After you have `enron-spam.zip` in the project root, extract it into a folder named `enron-spam/` in the same directory.

#### Linux / macOS (bash)

From the project root:

```bash
unzip enron-spam.zip -d enron-spam
```

#### Windows PowerShell

From the project root:

```powershell
Expand-Archive -Path .\enron-spam.zip -DestinationPath .\enron-spam -Force
```

After extraction, you should see something like:

```text
spamfilter/
  enron-spam.zip
  enron-spam/
    Enron_Txt_fn.csv
    ...
```

---

### Running the project

Assuming you have Go installed, from the project root you can run:

```bash
go run ./...
```

or:

```bash
go run main.go
```

For details on behavior, flags, or modes, check `main.go`.

---

### Notes / limitations

- **Very simple model**: basic bag-of-words, not tuned for accuracy.
- **No security guarantees**: do not expose this to untrusted input in production.
- **Not optimized**: may be slow or memory-heavy on large datasets.
- **Learning only**: intended for experimentation with Go and simple spam filtering ideas.
